Free translation of the narrative: "Building a Na house" In the past, our Na homes, the main house where the family lives had a room called a "ggaepae" [lit: upper area the storeroom for food, except grains, and other things], a room called a "mupae" [lit: lower area the kitchen where pig food is prepared], and a room called a "ddupae" [i.e. larder]. Three rooms! To begin with let's talk about these three rooms. When a house was being built, one would go to the mountain forests to cut timber. One would go to the mountain forests to cut timber at the beginning of the month. And one would stay for two or three months! For deciding the day for building the house, a lama would calculate an auspicious day! "Today is an auspicious day a day when the stars are good; let's go build the house!" If a person doesn't build on a good day when the stars are good and the night is good that's really bad, because he's going to live there his whole life! "One must not build indiscriminately [i.e. on an inauspicious day]!" the old people would say this in the past. So we'd get the lama to come and calculate the days [lit: stars], then he'd say, "This day is good, start building on the fifteenth day of the month!" Or, "Start building on the eighteenth day of the month!" Or, "Start building on the fifth day of the month!" Or, "Start building on the eighth day of the month!" In one month there are three auspicious days. Three auspicious days in one month! "In three auspicious days, during these three auspicious days, well, you mustn't miss this opportunity" said the lama. The building could begin! Well, for building a house, the timber all needs to be the same size. It must not be different lengths. So we cut down trees that are the same height. On the mountains, there is a terrific amount of wood! There are very many trees! When going to cut down a tree, you have to be careful of knots in the wood. If there are knots, it's because there are branches. You break off the branches. You cut down trees without too many big branches. If there are knots in the wood, cracks will appear later on. You choose trees without many knots; very tall trees, they don't have knots. [Note: The branches of very tall trees are near the tops of the trees; the lower part of the trunk, where there are few knots, is used in house building.] Really thick, thick wood, it's beautiful! Timber that has had its bark stripped off is beautiful like a person's washed face! On the mountains there's such good timber! Well, you have to choose which trees to cut down one by one. There's a terrific number of trees! Trees, on every mountain, there are so many! This one, it's good. That one, it's no good. This one's good. That one's no good. They'd choose like this, they'd look. There was someone who knew. [Note: This was usually a young man with carpentry skills.] The one who knew brought others along, looking and saying, "That one's good! Cut down that one!" pointing with his finger. "This one's good, cut it down!" he'd say, then they'd cut it down. Now, it was a skillful young man who would fell the tree, then square it up and throw it down. Timber that's good for building houses, you square it off, and when the home is built, if it gets water on it, it'll be waterproof. "This house of yours will be terrifically good, and if it gets water on it, it'll be waterproof!" they'd say. If it gets water on it, it won't leak. Done like this it's good, and not a bit of wind gets into the house. Because the timber is squared off like this, it really fits tightly together like this. Well, cut a bit here! Cut a bit there! In four directions like this. Then on one side you cut one half of the beam, make it bite together on one side. On the other side you cut one half of the beam, make it bite together on this side. Here one half, there one half, you need four halves [i.e. one beam for each of the four sides of the building]. There are four sides of timber, two long sides and two short sides, it's done just like this. Well, the timber is cut and brought back. It has to stay on the mountain for two months! Let it dry out on the mountain. In the past, I've done this! In the past I went with my great-uncles and uncles to cook for them. They went to the mountains to harvest timber. After cutting down timber on the mountain and placing it there, you leave it for two months! When it had been left to dry for two months, the timber on the high mountains was carried on the shoulders pile by pile, from place to place, and thrown down again here into the valley. Pulling and carrying timber, the logs had to be laid down one by one. Then they were grouped pile by pile, and when they were all piled up, they were carried on the shoulders from one place, carried on that mountain over there, and put on another mountain. [Note: The logs were moved in stages, coming down from mountain to mountain.] The hills were really, really high, and there were valleys like this! From there on, a rope was tied to the base of the timber at the place where it was cut, and it could be pulled. It's like people pulling on ropes to plough a field. Rrrr, rrrr! They'd pull the timber along, and arrive at the bottom, in a valley. In one day, they could pull one load of timber from a mountain down to a valley. Sometimes they'd have to pull the timber down five or six mountains! They'd pull it, and when they got to the bottom they'd arrive at the main road. They'd get to the main road, then carry the timber again on their backs, and from here carry it again on their backs. And now, having reached their destination, they'd throw the timber down beside the place where we were staying. They put the timber down here and here. They'd carry it on their shoulders to here, and then it's done. Once it'd been thrown down on the ground, all the timber for building the house was together in one place. Also the people who'd been cutting the timber would eat lunch there. Then, again and again, they'd carry, carry, carry the timber on their shoulders. Now, the road was about as long as from here to where Najjie and her colleagues work, at the Officials' Hotel! [Note: Najjie is one of the narrator's daughters. The hotel where she works is about two kilometres from the location where this recording was taking place.] Oh, it was a long way! Step by step from place to place a very long way, in this way they'd finally get there. Because it was it was so tough to get there like this, sometimes they'd need to be on the mountain for five or six nights. In the past, our building of a house was like this. When it was finished in this way, they arrived home! The day that they arrived home, they'd also calculate an auspicious day for building the house. When they arrived, people would say, "Wow! This year, mmm, it's a good year! The time has come to build a house! This year the time has come to build a house. It's a good year!" they'd say. In the past the old people would say, "Go consult the calendar! Which day will we build?" Each time they went to the mountains to cut down trees, they'd consult the calendar. They'd consult the stars! This is called, "Calculating the stars, calculating the days." We have this tradition. After the date for cutting down the trees had been chosen, they'd pull the timber back home from the mountains. Then, having arrived at the place where they wanted to live, they'd dig up a piece of ground. In the past, the Na would do this. Also, they'd go and show the lama, and then the lama would do the calculations: "Oh, this day, that place will be really good for you to build a house! Put the house here! Put the fireplace here!" he'd say. Also, "You should begin construction today," the lama would say, like this. Then construction would begin! So that day they'd build the house! In ten days it'd actually be built, the main part the core of the house. The frame of the house has twelve parts. If you count them one by one, its eighty two pieces! "How many pieces of framework are there in this house?" "There are twelve," they'd say! In the past, there really were set customs concerning building a house. Twelve framework parts. Install them in pairs. Four sides. Calculate the timber required and get it. It needs twelve parts. So, there are twelve framework parts. Once the twelve framework parts have been built, that's good. A whole pile of wood has been put in place. The house has been set up! Then, from there, the next stage is something called "zzho". [Note: These are square beams about 18cm in width that support the frame.] Oh, and pillars. My house has pillars, right? If the man was not very skilled, it'd be a bit angular not completely smooth. This side slanting. That side slanting. Incompetent men would make it like this. In the past, the Na, in order to find out if the people in a family were skilled or not, they'd go to their house and have a look at the pillars! In the past, the nobility looking at the quality of the pillars would say, "You've built such good pillars. Wow! In this family, there's an extremely skilled son, there's someone who's talented and skillful!" They'd say it like this. So that's how we'd do it, we'd erect the pillars! Once the pillars had been erected, on top of the pillars, there are beams. Na houses, they have everything! There's all sorts of stuff all over the place, on the whole. Beams, the ones used for houses, they're square like this. Well, one beam is put on each side like this, at the top. Have you seen them in my house? There, in that place, very big lengths of timber are used, a beam is put here, and that beam is put there. There are two beams. Two! Also, at the bottom of the building, the place where we cut up food to prepare for cooking, it is called "lhideemae" [i.e. the lower part of the main room]. There is also "the cat walking place". [Note: In the main room, there is an exposed beam near the top of the wall. Cats can walk here.] There is only one "cat walking place" in the whole house. Next there were also roof beams to be built. They're called "haenke"! Big pieces of timber cut into two halves, they're the beams. There are things called "rulee" [beams] in Na houses. It's a length of timber used in the building of a house. The things called "rulee", you need eighty lengths of timber for the whole house, you need eighty-six lengths of timber, and the roof beams, well, it seems they'd install fifty or sixty. The timber, the roof beams were actually installed in pairs or in threes, and when all the beams were finished being installed, the rafters would be put in place like this, one at a time. A layer of rafters was installed like this. Then the roofing boards were put up. [Note: These days roofing tiles are more readily available and cheaper than wooden roofing material, so the traditional techniques of laying wooden roofing are being lost.] So there you have it, a Na house! Then, after the roofing boards were finished being put up, the inside was constructed. The part built on the inside is also called the storeroom. The hearth is here, the back of the house here; my house has a storeroom, right? Also, there's a room called "mupae" [lit. bottom room]. It's where pig food is boiled up. Ah! In this room there was what was called the sleeping corner, in the past. Later too, there was what was called "ddupae" [the larder], behind the spot where you sit every day. [Note: The person recording the narrative would sit in a place in the main room where traditionally there would be a door opening to another room the larder.] Behind the bench where guests sit, there would be another room, in the past. [Note: In the narrator's home, the bench where guests sit is leaning against a wall, but traditionally there would be an extra room behind here for food storage.] After that, across the courtyard opposite the main building, there's also a building called "ggi" [the granary]. [Note: The fat and skin of a whole pig entrails, lean meat and bones having been removed is preserved with salt and sewn back up. It can be preserved in this way for several years. We Na, in the past we couldn't not have an altar to the ancestors in the home. That would be unthinkable! We Na, when someone dies, they're first put on the bed in the main room. Don't be in a rush to put the body into the coffin, they'd say. First build a bed [ i.e. in the main room, where the body could initially be put.] In the past, the body would be placed curled up there, in the place where dead people were put. For us Na, the concept of home is very important! We can't not have a home, it's said; in the past, no matter where you went, you'd first build a house! We'd build and build and build a house, and it was done! Once this was finished, we'd build the pig-food kitchen, we'd build the storeroom, then the day would come that the fire was lit, the day that we'd move into the home! The monks would be invited to come. Before moving into a new home, when the house is finished being built, we Na carry out a ritual called "ddaelaso". Two monks are called to come. The monks chant. To decide who will light the fire, the monk calculates the years [i.e. who was born in which year]. Someone born in the year of the tiger must light the fire! Or someone born in the year of the goat must light the fire! This is said to be very auspicious/good luck. A pot this large is put in place. The day that it's put in place, water is put into it. Mmmm, a chicken is killed, and a pig is killed on that day. People would say: "Wow! We're living in a new home! Our life is going to be really good!" and then they'd invite people in the village to come. Well, guests would bring gifts. They'd say: "Wow! You're living in a new home! You are so skilled to have done this! You've built such a beautiful house! You must be so happy to have such skilled children! Wow! Your new house is so beautiful!" This is how we Na, in the past, would do it. Then, when all this was finished, that night we'd sit together in the house and have a housewarming party. We'd say: "We have built a house! We are living in the new house," and we'd have a housewarming party. Then people would dance and dance, in the evening and into the night. The dance, it's part of the housewarming. For the housewarming party we'd sit together in the house. There are traditions! Talking all about houses, for each step there are traditions. There are traditions for building a house, how to do it, and for what is in the house! A house is not just about a building, it's not just about timber. You cut down timber, build a house, finish building the house, then there's all the household things in the house. We Na consider it very good to have copper objects in the home. People say, "Wow! These things, you have so many copper objects!" The morning that the fire is lit, the firepit is done, then there's the tripod. The tripod! It's big like this! There's one set up at my place, right? The tripod is installed by someone who was born in the year of the tiger or the goat. The person who was born in the year of the goat, they put the water in. The person born in the year of the goat is very good. A goat can eat anything, then it goes to sleep. Now, a person born in the year of the goat will have plenty. They will have plenty! The person born in the year of the tiger, wherever they seek they will find what they were looking for. This person is very skilled, it was said in the past. There is a proverb about this. The person born in the year of the tiger, the person born in the year of the horse, the person born in the year of the goat, these three. Well, the nanny goat eats food and then sleeps [i.e. lacks nothing]. She eats and is satisfied. The person born in the year of the tiger, well, they seek and wherever they look, they find. Ah, the year of the tiger is good! The person born in the year of the horse, it's said they can carry and bring back a lot of stuff. Long ago there was a proverb that said this. So then, the building of a house was done like this, and doing it made people extremely tired. In the past, I went to help in the building of a house. Carrying, carrying, carrying timber, your shoulders would be swollen. Well, we'd rub in a bit of alcohol. This alcohol was made at home and brought with us, bottles and bottles of alcohol. The alcohol would be put into little jars. There were no plastic containers like there are now. The alcohol was carried in little jars, they were things called "lage". Well, when we went into the mountains to cut down timber, there was often no water. There was no water! There were no plastic buckets like these days! Water was carried on our backs in bamboo baskets. These bamboo baskets, in the past they were called "khuatu". They were woven! The things for putting water into, the old people had them. The water had to be carried on the back for long distances. Water was carried on the back in a bamboo basket. Then it was put down and food was cooked. Wow! The people who carried water on their backs, they often carried it from way down the bottom right up to the top where the timber was being cut! They had to carry it over two sections of road to reach the top. One person who cooked the food, and one person who carried the water. Well, in the past, there were all sorts of animals in the mountain forests. There were leopards! There were tigers! There were wolves! Leopards and tigers, wolves, rabbits, oh! And foxes! Wow! Wherever you looked, it was scary, scary, so scary! Because there were so many trees, you couldn't see anything, I couldn't see anything. Wow, it was so scary! We hoped we would quickly get to a road. There was hill after hill, so people could only really make a narrow road. Here were trees! There were trees! Also, in the mountain forests there was a type of squirrel. With their long, long tails, there were many of them. "Bububu," they'd go, running here, "bububu", running there. They were terrified of people and would run away in fear. Then, one place after another, the trees they'd go "crrrrack, crrrack!" People would wonder to themselves if there was a tiger in the area, that would be so terrifying! I've stayed overnight in the mountain forests in the past, with my great uncle and my uncles. I went to cook meals and wash vegetables. In the past, we the Latami family we built very many houses. Wow! We built very many, and pulled all that timber down from the mountains. We pulled timber down for a month! We got to the riverbank, and then threw the logs into the river. We made the logs float on the water. [Note: This was done during the rainy season when the river was in full flood, e.g. during the fifth or sixth month of the lunar calendar.] All that water, and pulling timber as far as the river bank. There was one year when bandits were attacking. If bandits attack, it's a fight, right? Good people and bad people fight each other! Fighting, those bandits, wow! At that time, it seems that there were a few people from the Communist Party. There was a school building that the Communist Party were going to build. It's said that the timber for the building was all burned up by the bandits! The timber was taken as far as the river bank. Well, my great-grandmother wept, "Alas, alas! My wooden beams are gone! My beautiful building has been burned down." She wept and wept, and we said, "Don't worry, great-grandmother! Good times will come again. You will be housed in a beautiful house. Don't worry! These days, this bad time will be no more. At the moment it's a bit of a tough time, but this building was not ours anyway!" The timber on the riverbank was all burned up by the robbers who were in the mountains! In the past thieves were called "robbers", these days they're called "bandits" [i.e. a Chinese loanword tufei]. Robbers stole people's belongings; whatever they saw, they would steal. If they saw timber, they would burn it! If they saw goats, they would take away the goats! If they saw cattle, they would take the cattle away! In this way, they set fire to everything on the mountains! If they set fire to my house, it would be gone! Truly, then, you'd have to build another home, or else you'd have to buy one, it truly was like this. In the past, our family built three houses. Three! I know about these things. It was like this, in the past. In the mountain areas, it was really difficult! The people who went to the mountain forests, the old people, wow! When evening came, they were so, so tired! They were too exhausted to eat, in those days. They'd boil up a slab of pork fat and a pot of rice. They'd boil up a pot of dehydrated vegetables. On the mountains! And then they'd pour one bowl of alcohol per person to drink. So, it was like this, building a house. They were all built according to the same model! New Na houses were modelled on existing houses. Among the Na, there are none who don't have a house. These days, if a Na home doesn't have a storeroom and a pig-food kitchen, that's no good. There must be a storeroom, there must be a pig-food kitchen! Also, at the back there must be a larder. The main room itself is not the whole house, there are three parts. The other parts are connected like this to the main room. One piece is connected on this side. One piece is connected at the back. The main room is here; the storeroom, it's connected here; the pig-food kitchen, it's connected here; the larder, it's connected here. The whole house is connected like this. Na houses, if you counted it all up, there was a lot of wood! There really was a lot of wood used to build a house in the past.
